    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-05-20T21:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-05-20T21:00:00-05:00" n="631"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d631">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.203/284: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Atcheson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-05-21T09:00:00+07:00"
                            >May 21, 1943—9 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 9:35 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>748. Embassy’s 725, May 17, 2 p.m.<note n="9" xml:id="d631fn9">Not
                        printed.</note> At the Foreign Office this morning May 21 Kuo Cheng Wu (Dr.
                    K. C. Wu) and I signed and exchanged the notes on military jurisdiction<note
                        n="10" xml:id="d631fn10">For text, see Department of State Executive
                        Agreement Series No. 360, or 57 Stat. 1248.</note> as set forth in the
                    telegram under reference. Both notes were accompanied by agreed upon Chinese
                    translations which were also signed at the request of Dr. Wu who stated that
                    this was contemplated in the oral arrangements previously come to with the
                    Embassy.</p>
                <p>Dr. Wu stated that the Foreign Office plans to publish the notes in the Chinese
                    press tomorrow with a short explanation to the effect that they constitute an
                    arrangement similar to arrangements entered into between the United States and
                    various countries during the last war and also entered into between the United
                    States and Great Britain and a number of other countries during the present
                    war.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Atcheson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
